summary: Arya told Sansa she was training all that time? She should've just told her the real thing. Arya suffered just as much as Sansa,...
body:
Arya told Sansa she was training all that time? She should’ve just told her the real thing. Arya suffered just as much as Sansa, just in a different way.

If Tywin found out about her real identity or if she was captured during the Red Wedding or if the Hound didn’t show up in time when she was running away, what do you think was gonna happen? For fucks sake, remember her face when she saw Robb’s body with Grey Wind’s head?

summary: Arya stalked away angry, and would have slammed the door if it hadn’t been so heavy. Darkness had settled over Acorn Hall. A few...
text:
Arya stalked away angry, and would have slammed the door if it hadn’t been so heavy. Darkness had settled over Acorn Hall. A few torches burned along the walls, but that was all. The gates of the little castle were closed and barred. She had promised Harwin that she would not try and run away again, she knew, but that was before they started telling lies about her mother.
“Arya?” Gendry had followed her out. “Lady Smallwood said there’s a smithy. Want to have a look?”
“If you want.” She had nothing else to do.

summary: lil love letter to game of thrones[[MORE]] Season One of game of thrones came out two days before my 19th birthday in so many...
body:
lil love letter to game of thrones

Season One of game of thrones came out two days before my 19th birthday
in so many ways i was still just a kid trying to find her place in the world
and this show provided a whole cast of strong women who started out as absolute nobodies
that overcame these absolutely horrifying obstacles
and unlike some of the other shows, movies, and books i like and love - they didn’t have any superpowers helping them. like yeah it’s surreal and they absolutely had supernatural skills (in the books arya can warg) but it’s still not the same as having something like ‘the force’ or whatever.

beyond me being a tomboyish brown-haired left handed fencer that loves wolves, and arya also being a tomboyish brown-haired kind of scrawny left-handed swordswoman, there was a lot i could relate to in that character. arya learned to fight and eventually could level with anyone bigger or stronger than her, but it didn’t happen all at once. she learned from several teachers along the way. she had to be humbled quite a bit but she became formidable as time went on and i really related – relate – to her tenacity and grit - to her connection with wolves, to her adaptability. regardless of what some people will say she also never lost her compassion or her identity despite becoming a darker character, and only took out people she thought deserved it. she learned to exist and thrive in a world kind of hell bent on pushing her down and in a less lethal way i deal with that quite a bit in the biological sciences. people sort of want to see you fail and if you want to succeed you need to learn how to develop foresight.

when i had to start dealing with death more in my job - i work with wildlife - i at least had game of thrones?? weird, right? but like ‘what do we say to the god of death’ ‘not today’ really resonated with me and helped me put my feelings away and tackle some really crazy cases. and the idea of ‘valar morghulis valar dohaeris’ helped me deal with the ones i couldn’t control; the times i unfortunately felt forced to act against my own instincts or even my sense of right and wrong. or the times i messed up, because that happens too sometimes.

i always found a mirror in game of thrones. so i’m really sad to see it end. in a way i grew up with the show, with the protagonists. so now i’m a real adult and occasionally successful and i don’t need a fictional mirror as much anymore. i know there will always be relatable characters out there. beyond that i guess after this it’s time to wait for george rr martin’s next book lol

title: You Win Or You Die: Game Of Thrones: Seasons 6 & 7
body:
One more check in before the final season of #GameOfThrones

There’s a moment in Act II of the brilliant musical Follies where the character of Buddy pokes his head out and exclaims, “Alright folks! We’re into the Follies now.” This moment is when Follies leaves behind any resemblance to a traditional book musical and becomes a series of sketches until it’s finale.

I think about this moment a lot when it comes to television, particularly long running TV,…
